2026-04-30 21:20:45,671 [ERROR] vlm: VLM call failed: Could not parse JSON from VLM response: '## Step 1: Understand the given problem\nThe problem provides a limit equation involving real numbers $\\alpha$ and $\\beta$, and we need to find the value of $\\alpha + \\beta$. The given limit is:\n\\[\n\\lim_{x \\to 0} \\frac{1}{x^3} \\left( \\frac{\\alpha}{2} \\int_{0}^{x} \\frac{1}{1-t^2} dt + \\beta x \\cos x \\right) = 2.\n\\]\n\n## 2: Evaluate the integral\nFirst, let\'s evaluate the integral $\\int_{0}^{x} \\frac{1}{1-t^2} dt$. This is a standard integral which can be solved using partial fractions:\n\\[\n\\int \\frac{1}{1-t^2} dt = \\int \\left( \\frac{1}{1-t} + \\frac{1}{1+t} \\right) dt = -\\ln|1-t| + \\ln|1+t| + C.\n\\]\nEvaluating from 0 to $x$:\n\\[\n\\int_{0}^{x} \\frac{1}{1-t^2} dt = \\left[ \\ln \\left| \\frac{1+t}{1-t} \\right| \\right]_{0}^{x} = \\ln \\left| \\frac{1+x}{1-x} \\right| - \\ln 1 = \\ln \\left( \\frac{1+x}{1-x} \\right).\n\\]\n\n## 3: Apply the limit\nNow, substitute the integral back into the limit:\n\\[\n\\lim_{x \\to 0} \\frac{1}{x^3} \\left( \\frac{\\alpha}{2} \\ln \\left( \\frac{1+x}{1-x} \\right) + \\beta x \\cos x \\right) = 2.\n\\]\nTo solve this, we can use series expansions for $\\ln \\left( \\frac{1+x}{1-x} \\right)$ and $\\cos x$.\n\n## 4: Series expansions\nThe series expansion for $\\ln(1+x)$ is $x - \\frac{x^2}{2} + \\frac{x^3}{3} - ...$ and for $\\ln(1-x)$ is $-x - \\frac{x^2}{2} - \\frac{x^3}{3} - ...$. Thus,\n\\[\n\\ln \\left( \\frac{1+x}{1-x} \\right) = \\ln(1+x) - \\ln(1-x) = \\left( x - \\frac{x^2}{2} + \\frac{x^3}{3} - ... \\right) - \\left( -x - \\frac{x^2}{2} - \\frac{x^3}{3} - ... \\right)\n\\]\n\\[\n= 2x + \\frac{2x^3}{3} + ...\n\\]\nAnd $\\cos x = 1 - \\frac{x^2}{2} + ...$.\n\n## 5: Substitute series expansions into the limit\nSubstituting these into the limit:\n\\[\n\\lim_{x \\to 0} \\frac{1}{x^3} \\left( \\frac{\\alpha}{2} \\left( 2x + \\frac{2x^3}{3} \\right) + \\beta x \\left( 1 - \\frac{x^2}{2} \\right) \\right) = 2.\n\\]\nSimplifying:\n\\[\n\\lim_{x \\to 0} \\frac{1}{x^3} \\left( \\alpha x + \\frac{\\alpha x^3}{3} + \\beta x - \\frac{\\beta x^3}{2} \\right) = 2.\n\\]\n\\[\n\\lim_{x \\to 0} \\frac{1}{x^3} \\left( (\\alpha + \\beta)x + \\left( \\frac{\\alpha}{3} - \\frac{\\beta}{2} \\right) x^3 \\right) = 2.\n\\]\n\n## 6: Solve for $\\alpha$ and $\\beta$\nFor the limit to exist, the coefficient of $x$ must be 0, so $\\alpha + \\beta = 0$.\nThe coefficient of $x^3$ gives:\n\\[\n\\frac{\\alpha}{3} - \\frac{\\beta}{2} = 2.\n\\]\nNow we have two equations:\n1. $\\alpha + \\beta = 0$\n2. $\\frac{\\alpha}{3} - \\frac{\\beta}{2} = 2$\n\n## 7: Solve the system of equations\nFrom equation 1: $\\beta = -\\alpha$.\nSubstituting into equation 2:\n\\[\n\\frac{\\alpha}{3} - \\frac{-\\alpha}{2} = 2\n\\]\n\\[\n\\frac{\\alpha}{3} + \\frac{\\alpha}{2} = 2\n\\]\n\\[\n\\frac{2\\alpha + 3\\alpha}{6} = 2\n\\]\n\\[\n5\\alpha = 12\n\\]\n\\[\n\\alpha = \\frac{12}{5}\n\\]\nThen $\\beta = -\\frac{12}{5}$.\n\n## 8: Calculate $\\alpha + \\beta$\n\\[\n\\alpha + \\beta = \\frac{12}{5} - \\frac{12}{5} = 0\n\\]\n\nThe answer is {"answer": "0", "confidence": 90}'
