-\\frac{1}{50}\\right| = \\frac{1}{50} \\, \\text{m/s}^2\\]\n\n## 6: Calculate the maximum variation of the object\'s weight\nThe weight \\(W\\) of an object in an elevator is given by \\(W = m(g + a)\\), where \\(m = 50 \\, \\text{kg}\\) and \\(g = 10 \\, \\text{m/s}^2\\). The maximum variation in weight occurs when \\(a = a_{max}\\) or \\(a = -a_{max}\\).\n\n## 7: Compute the maximum weight variation\nThe maximum weight \\(W_{max} = m(g + a_{max}) = 50(10 + \\frac{1}{50})\\) and the minimum weight \\(W_{min} = 50(10 - \\frac{1}{50})\\). The variation in weight is:\n\\[\\Delta W = 50(10 + \\frac{1}{50}) - 50(10 - \\frac{1}{50})\\]\n\\[\\Delta W = 50 \\cdot 10 + 50 \\cdot \\frac{1}{50} - 50 \\cdot 10 + 50 \\cdot \\frac{1}{50}\\]\n\\[\\Delta W = 2 \\cdot 50 \\cdot \\frac{1}{50}\\]\n\\[\\Delta W = 2\\]\n\nThe final answer is: \n{"answer": "2", "confidence": 90}'
